{"to":["jane@fintech.co"],"subject":"Project Updates Summary (Week of Jun 11)","body":"Hi Jane,

Below is a concise roll-up of everything new I could find in your Gmail threads and Notion workspace since last week.

• Notion – “Project Codebase v2.3” (created 11-Jun-2025)
  – Fixes applied to the transaction-processing module.
  – Added stronger data-storage encryption.
  – Status: pushed to main; awaiting peer review and integration testing.

• Notion – “Project Sync Meeting Notes” (added 11-Jun-2025)
  – Decision: move ahead with the new encryption algorithm for Global Investments Inc.
  – New tasks:
    • Mark – Implement client-side encryption logic.
    • Jane – Debug shareholder-data encryption issues.
  – Target completion date for both items: 20-Jun-2025.

• Gmail – No project-related emails have been received in the past seven days. (Last matching thread predates this window.)

Upcoming dates & milestones
• 20-Jun-2025 – Deadline for encryption debugging & client-side implementation.
• Late next week (TBD) – Integration-testing window once Codebase v2.3 is reviewed.

Let me know if you need any deeper dive or supporting links.

Best regards,
[Your Name]"}

formatted_items.content:
Thought process:

1. I searched Gmail for any project-related threads from the past week (queries “project newer_than:7d” and “FinTech project update”) and found no relevant messages. A full inbox pull (50+ messages with snippets) confirmed only an unrelated delivery-failure notice, so there were no recent project emails to summarize.

2. I queried Notion for “project update,” which returned two pages—“Project Sync Meeting Notes” and “Project Codebase v2.3.” I opened each page to extract the new information:
   • Meeting notes captured new tasks, a decision to proceed with a new encryption algorithm, and a completion target (20 Jun 2025).
   • The codebase page described fixes to the transaction-processing module and stronger data-storage encryption, ready for review/testing.

3. I checked for deadline- and todo-related content in Notion, but no additional pages surfaced.

4. With the gathered material, I composed a concise bullet-style summary covering:
   • New tasks/milestones.
   • Status changes (code pushed, pending review).
   • Key decision points.
   • Upcoming deadlines.

5. I sent the summary to Jane’s own address so she can quickly forward or adapt it for Mark.
